segments.text: Saturdays and Sundays and after school.
Then the next year I decided that I could learn to type and I would learn to type and I'd get me a job at the courthouse.
Well, I only had a hunt and pick system of typing
And when I went to work, they put me to, I always had a fairly good legible hand, and they put me to copying off the evaluation on the evaluation sheets of the county in the sheriff's office.
And then I did that for four years.
And then I got married.
And from then on, I did just a little bit of that.
I clerked and I stole them.
And then I stood for a step and taught school.
Then I decided that was too hard.
After I taught, let's see, I taught four years.
And then I had a little boy.
And I stayed at home with him until he was ready to go to school.
And then I went, that was in 45, 36, well, I went back.
Just got my certificate.
Finished out the superintendency and the principal, taught again.
Then I was city tax assessor, the first woman to ever hold office in Johnson City.
City tax assessor and collector.
That was when we started to organize the city.
And I took up the taxes, did the assessing and whatnot for the city.
And then I decided to go to college in 48.
And I went down and took 12 hours.
And I made the A honor roll, which I got to take an extra three hours if you carry the B honor roll system.
So I made an A, so I got to carry it.
Then in the fall, I came back and started teaching school again.
and go to school every night at Trinity.
I'd catch the 6 o'clock.
No, at that time it ran at 2.30, and my first grade was out at 2.30, and the bus stopped right over here where the U-Totem is.
It was not a U-Totem then, but it was a big grocery store.
And I would meet the bus there and get on it from school and go to San Antonio to Trinity University.
And I'd catch the bus out at 12 o'clock at night and come back to Johnson City and get to school the next morning at 8.
I learned to read on the bus and I learned to study on the bus.
That's how I kept going until I got my degree.
That's why I say when I lose faith, I remember you.
And then on Saturdays, I always had all-day classes on Saturday.
Every Saturday I had all-day classes.
Sunday was the only day I had an offer to study for preparation.
That was to keep up my schoolwork and everything else.
It's a lot of determination.
And to sell yourself that you can do it.
And you're as smart as the next one.
You may not be.
But if you can sell yourself that you can do it, then you will.
Yeah.
It was a hard thing for me to do, to sell myself that I was as smart as Kitty Clyde or I was as smart as Margaret or as Linda.
I could do anything they could do.
Now, that's not a job.
But I backed my ears and did it.
And at the same time, I think you enjoyed life, too.
I did.
I enjoyed going to school.
I enjoyed learning.
It was a wonderful thing to me.
It just gave me a different outlook on life altogether.
And I look back today and think, well, how fortunate I was just to make myself do the thing that couldn't be done.
And I did it.
And I'm proud of it.
I think so.
But you came from a different background, and your roots were...
I mean, you learned the history you live now.
You bet.
You know that.
That's right, too.
That's quite a musty one for candy.
Well, honey, I've got some homemade candy.
Oh, no, no, no, no.
I just needed one little piece of candy.
If you break out the candy, I'm going to break out the weight.
Well, here's all kinds of dookie candy.
Oh, no.
Look at that.
Porcupines.
Come on, Steve.
One.
Oh, no.
That's got dates in it and everything else.
No, it don't.
Double dates and that.
What does it have?
Well, something you wouldn't even think about, couldn't you?
There's no telling.
It looks good.
Of course it's good.
What's wrong with you?
I'm going to ask you a question.
How long did you live before you had the electricity to live with?
I mean, that's just a simple thing that everybody takes for granted.
Well, honey, I was born in 1905, and we didn't have any electricity here until the 40s.
That's what I thought.
All right.
Can you add, subtract, or multiply?
Mm-hmm.
There you are.
That's how long, I know.
We had a...
I wanted to hear you say it.
Down at the ranch, we had a carbide light plant.
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
We used that every once in a while, but not very often.
Most of the time it's coal oil because carbide was very expensive for us to buy.
Now, we just didn't have it all the time.
That's the way it was.
My daddy went through this country talking to people and buying up easements where they also already put their lines through you.
And you know some of them were so bitter against it that he took an act of Congress to get them to sign an easement to go over their land.
That's how far back we were.
Life was just slow.
Yes, ma'am.
They say the 20th century didn't get to Texas until the 40s in many ways.
That's right.
40s and 50s in some places up here.
You bet.
Very true.
I mean, but it's not that the people are backwards.
It's that the people were in a time frame that is, was a time frame that we lived with a lot longer than we've lived with the time frame we're in now, right?
That's right.
I mean, that's electricity.
We did not live beyond our means.
No.
And we didn't have it.
We couldn't produce it.
But you were not a backwards people.
No, we were never backwards.
And even though we didn't have
radios until late.
And we didn't have electricity.
We didn't have any of the finer things of life.
And our mail, our newspapers were weekly.
And no, well, the only freight we had was on a flatbed truck, and that didn't come in here until in the 30s.
And the
15s and 20s is all done by horse and mule and wagon and we just lived in a time that you grew your food and you lived off of the land and you didn't you didn't spend
money.
You didn't have it.
And there wasn't something to run out of your five minutes and spend it on?
No, sir.
No, you didn't.
You take your eggs and your milk, or I mean your eggs and your cream and your butter to town and you sold it.
You bought that much beans and you had your bacon and
You had your eggs.
You brought your wheat into town.
Right down there at that cross mill was a gin and a mill, flour mill and a corn mill.
You'd bring them into town.
You had your own flour.
You had your own mill.
You bought your sugar by 100 pounds, and that would last you a whole year.
That's right.
That's it.
Because you used sardine and molasses, and you used honey for your sweetening a lot.
You didn't use sugar like we do it today.
No.
That's an intake.
That's right.
And you lived at home.
Let me ask you a question.
I remember even when you speak about your mother, you told me that she spent a lot of time, even though she had a hard life, writing songs.
She did.
She had some of the prettiest songs.
I've read some of them.
And I would love to have copies of all those.
My daddy and my mother sang together beautifully.
I'm telling you.
Now, that's happy memories.
That's living.
When the night work was over and everything was done, we had a great long porch at the ranch in the summertime.
We'd sit out there.
And she would pick the guitar and they would sing.
And she'd put it down and maybe just, they'd just sing without it.
And, you know, we listened to them.
And we thought that they were just, that was just something wonderful.
And it was.
It is.
And you look back and you really enjoy it.
And we'd get ready to go to bed.
I think of the Waltons.
Well, they'll say goodnight to all of them.
Well, in place of that, mother always sat in a rocking chair, and my daddy sat in a straight back chair.
And we'd go by, and we'd kiss mother goodnight.
And she'd say, now sweet dreams, but I'll be in to hear your prayers.
Didn't make any difference how cold, how wet, or whatnot, or how tired.
That was ritual with mother.
We said our prayers.
And he wasn't now laying me down to sleep.
It was really a little prayer.
But it always wound up.
Make me a good girl.
Make me a better girl.
Make me mind my mother.
That was two things.
Not that she told us, but she'd tell us.
You pray for the things that you know you need.
And that was one of them.
Make me a better girl.
Help me to mind my mother.
Mother told us that she told us not to do something.
She said, every time you don't do it, when I tell you, you'll have trouble.
And honest to goodness, that was just as sure as shooting that happened.
Made her believe her.
But that was one of the things that, to me, was the happiest times of my life.
We didn't have a whole lot.
We had a lot of love.
And you can take a lot of hardship as long as you've got love.
But your mother came from a loving family, didn't she?
Was your mom's family a hard life family?
Well, grandfather and grandmother always had more than a good living.
But they were good managers.
My daddy, bless his heart, he was the sweetest thing that ever lived.
And he never met a person that he couldn't see some good in.
I don't care who he was.
I never heard my father say there wasn't some good in the worst people.
He loved everybody.
And he was his own worst enemy.
Uncle Tom, I want to borrow some money today.
Well, how much do you need?
Run down his pocket.
Maybe the last time he'd see Uncle Tom.
That'd be it.
He was, that's the way it went.
And I can remember, I'll never forget if I lived to be a thousand years old.
After my father had been dead about two weeks,

mother and i were in town mother didn't like to drive and i went down the range and brought her in she wanted to attend some business i met one of the corley boys he says aunt kitty i want to see you just a minute he walked over of course aunt kitty and uncle tom that was the way affectionately everyone spoke of them and
Mama said, well, what is it that you need or you want?
He said, Uncle Tom loaned me $5 before he died, that two weeks, and said, I want to pay you back.
If she could have collected a third of what she had, that was just one of the good ones that came across.
And was less able to pay than any that I know of that was on the books.
But yet he paid his.
But so many of the others felt like that mother never knew it.
Yes, forgot it.
But this was her house, right?
She built this house after 35.
Mm-hmm.

Really good.

Well, probably so.
I am too.
So what time are you going to go down tomorrow?
I don't know.
They keep doing what I get up for.
What I have to get up for.
True.
You're a lady of leisure now.
Hmm.
I'm not a lady of leisure or pleasure, but I'm not going to get up early.
If I get up 8 o'clock, that's fine.
That sounds good.
I don't see any use in getting up early.
You've gotten up early long enough.
You've spent half your life getting up early.
This morning I got up at 3 o'clock and set my yeast.
That's right.
I baked three loaves of bread this morning.
And forgot it.
You know what I mean?
And I let it rise too, and it's going to be wasp nasty.
But that's all right.
It's going to eat.
I'm not going to do away with it.
It's going to be coarse-poured.
The other I have in there is real fine.
It's nice.
I didn't let it rise too.
I forgot it.
Yeah, and he called me at Fredericksburg and he said,
I know you have a good job, and I know you're satisfied.
But there's one thing I want you to do for me.
And I know you can do it."
And I said, well, Linda, what in the world could that be?
He said, I want you to go into San Antonio.
And then it was a job, on-the-job training program that he put out.
And you see, and you get jobs for these little boys and girls in San Antonio that are capable and willing to work and place them.
And I want you to do that.
And I said, well, what district, what part of San Antonio?
Well, that was over in the Edgewood District, and that was one of the poorest districts.
And boy, I never worked as hard in all my life as I did right there.
But it paid dividends.
I grant you.
But for the same token, it was one of the hardest things I ever tried to do in my life.
And that's why I was in second grade teacher.
And then I worked there a couple of years.
And I said, now that's sufficient.
I'm going.
So I went to the north side.
And there's where I finished up.
And I helped open up the Lackawanna City Elementary School.
And then when they opened up Collins North, my principal said, he went over to open it up.
He said, well, I have to have some old teachers that know what they're doing to put this thing on the right track.
He said, if I open this up, can I pick my teachers?
And the superintendent of the district said, yes.
Well, I was picked to go over there.
And then that was another thing.
We had a program.
that we taught really it was things that should have been taught in the home but we had it at school and it was more or less on self-rule and
Now do you think, if you do this, do you think that all the others are going to accept that and that's the way to treat people?

And those little sixth graders, man, they would ante up right quick and they fell in line with all this self-discipline and you'd walk in that realm of mind if I were not there and you could hear a pin drop.
Because one would call down the other and say, no, that's not right, don't do that.
Miss Abel won't like that.
That's not the way we're supposed to do it.
Do you think they'd cut in line for one another?
That's not right.
You're infringing on the other folks.
He was there first.
Don't get in front of him.
Get behind him.
Take your turn.
And things like that.
And they would get in, and I'd give them the opportunity to discuss all major problems that came out in the paper of a morning.
What do you think about this?
Are they handling this right?
They were taught to rely on their own judgment.
And how to do that.
Then I was put over to the district.
He really just picked me up and said, now you go do this.
That's how I went.
He respected your opinions.
He didn't know he was listening to them.
Well, he didn't to a great extent, yet he did in the long run, too.
He loved me, and I know it, and I loved him.
We'd fuss and we'd fight.
But by the same token, blood runs deeper than water.
They might be meeting today, but any time they do, they're...
When they began to down him and say, he did this, I can name so many good things that he did, that we have quite a battle.

and I believe as strong as I believe that the sun will come up in the east tomorrow that history will deal with him as a good president and not as a falsifying president I may not ever see the day or know it but I believe that truly there isn't a president living or dead
That you can't go back and find the skeleton in that closet if you look there from far enough and deep enough.
And he's no exception to the rule.
But right now they make it as though it's a mountain and that's a bunch of balloon.
It's newsworthy and sellable, right?
Well, I don't know whether it's even... People much rather read something about a president that talks about his mistakes than about his successes.
That is success.
That is very true.
And it's always better than good for reading.
You bet.
But as I said before, we had such a hard time getting an education.
We didn't have free school.
That was out.
It was a five-month school, and if you could do it in five months, you were good.
And if you couldn't, well, that was bad.
But they'd make an effort.
Our parents make all the effort in the world to send us to school at seven months.
But both of them on each side of the house being teachers, it wasn't no problem to keep us at home and make us do our work.
So we were not too handicapped in lots of respects.
But it just burns me up to think that a kid will lay out of school when the bus comes to his door and pick him up and we'd have to ride horseback and take our cold lunch and
time we'd lope a horse and it'd joke up and down and be all crumbs when we'd get here and we'd eat it or do it that.
And then these kids lazy things can't even get there on time.
Shh.
I just don't.
I don't have any patience with people like that.
Well, I guess it sounds better.
You better cut your deal off.
Why?

You want to talk to me for a while?
Well, I will if you've got a bet.
Sure.
If that's what you want.
Well, I think we ought to.
I just... Might as well continue talking.
Well, it's whatever you want.
Well, it seems it's going to be a book, so might as well.

I'll have them transcribed.
I told that to Pat.

Well, I don't know.

You can't count on the future.
Oh, that's right, too.
And good seeds somewhere along the way that'll turn out just like you.

I said, Corky, how many times have I pointed out to you and told you things along this highway that...
No historian has ever put down at all.
I know.
And it's time that somebody do it.
That's right.
Now, that old Oddfellow building over at Round Mountain.
Yeah, I remember that.
The Oddfellow's Lodge had a 99-year lease on that.
Did it?
And it will be up in, well, 19...
I believe it's 1990.
I believe that's when the lease is up.
But of course they've sold it.
We have no odd fellows here.
But that still doesn't give a clear title and a clear lead to it until this is all set aside.
Now they've improved it and worked it, but that was a liver stable underneath it.
All right, there's very few people really know what a liver stable was.
Of this generation that's growing up.
And the stalls were there, and it really was a pony express.
I can remember when they would bring things from the mail carrier to this, from Marble Falls to Johnson City that was carried in a hack.
Right.
Just a plain old hat.
And that was when Roy Stubbs would come by and say, come on, kids.
Tom loaned one of these kids to me to help ferry this mail across down here at this crossing.
Why?
Children don't know what ferrying a male across the crossing is.
Well, they don't teach it to you in history classes now.
I mean, the naivety that goes out from the professor's mouth to the student is a crime.
They don't talk about those things.
No, they don't.
I've got to tell you something real quick.
I thought about you doing something for me also, which would be very beneficial, is if we could sit down and have you tell a straight segment of history, such as ferry crossing, such as cattle,
as your gift to students in the future.
Have you thought about doing that?
No, I haven't.
I thought that I cannot do it.

You would be the one to say, just as if you were standing in front of a mirror yourself and setting this tape down and recording what you would be teaching a group of children about history in Blanco County.
I think that this could be a beneficial segment of historic tapes to be used in classrooms.
And I would like to ask you to do it, because if I decide not to go into something like social work or something, I'm going to go right on back into the classroom.
And I know that it would be a marvelous segment to go along with teaching students, because if I teach, it's going to be social studies.
Now, Annie, do you know that because we didn't have
any railroad connection.
And the only reason it was one at Marble Falls, and it was laid down for the purpose of carrying the granite to build the capital at Austin.
Now that was reason for that.
Because they quarried it in Marble Falls, and they sent it to Austin.
That's right.
And they sent it in to Austin.
That was after they ran out of the limestone, and that's what was first to be built out of was limestone.
worked at three different quarries to get this, and they didn't have enough.
So they, Dara's, offered the granite if they would send the labor.
So the Texas prison guards were sent out there to cut the... Oh, yeah.

They dug tunnels back in there.
Sure they have.
And they were...
That was one of them.

Sure.

It would be very beneficial.
